<p class="">Gov. Abubakar Bello of Niger on Wednesday said that the state government would inaugurate a committee to discuss with the organised labour on how to implement the new N30,000 minimum wage.</p> <p class="">Bello, who was not specific on when the committee would come, made this known in Minna during the 2019 May Day celebration.</p> <p class=""><em>â€œI have listened to the demands of the Nigeria Labour Congress (NLC) chairman. We will not promise to solve all your problems in one day but to take them according to priority.</em></p> <p class=""><em>â€œWe will inaugurate a committee to initiate discussion with the organised labour on how to implement the N30,000 new minimum wage recently signed into law by President Muhammadu Buhari,</em>â€� he said.</p> <p class="">He said that government was making plans to increase its Internal Generated Revenue (IGR) to cater for workers welfare and development of the state.</p> <p class="">â€œ<em>As we plan to increase our IGR we will see how we can make you comfortable,</em>â€� he said.</p> <p class="">The Governor said that the state would cut unnecessary spending in the system to be able to maintain the new minimum wage.</p> <p class="">He advised civil servants against financial coruption in the system to enable Government carry out meaningful development.</p> <p class="">â€œ<em>We crave your indulgence and support to help us succeed in this direction,</em>â€� he said.</p> <p class="">Bello said that in the past four years Government has spent N25.7 billion on payment of gratuities and pensions of retirees.</p> <p class="">On payment of incomplete salary affecting some workers recently, he directed the state Head of Civil Service, Alhaji Yabagi Sule to ensure that the mistake was corrected before the end of May.</p> <p class="">â€œ<em>The Head of Service told me that the mistake was a computer error. If the error repeats itself by the end of this month it will be no longer computer error but human error,</em>â€� he